The white motor connector on the shield is labeled:
M4- M4+ M3- M3+

========================================================================

Motor Driver Chip
The shield normally uses two L293D motor driver chips.
Each chip controls two motors.
Chip	Controls
IC1	M1 and M2
IC2	M3 and M4
From the board:
IC1 socket is empty
Only IC2 is installed
Therefore:
Motor	Status
M1	Not usable
M2	Not usable
M3	Working
M4	Possibly damaged (Since it not working at all)

Arduino Pin Mapping
The UC-435 motor shield maps motors to Arduino pins like this:
Motor	Direction Pins	Speed (PWM) Pin
M1	D8, D11	D9
M2	D12, D13	D10
M3	D4, D7	D6
M4	D2, D3	D5
Since M3 works, I use
Direction: pins 4 and 7
Speed: pin 6
========================================================================

Motor Direction Logic

For DC motors:
IN1 HIGH + IN2 LOW  → forward
IN1 LOW + IN2 HIGH  → backward
Speed is controlled by PWM:
analogWrite(enablePin, speed)
Speed range:
0   = stop
255 = full speed

Code that works for now 
Working Motor Test Code

This code drives Motor M3 only.

int M3_IN1 = 4;
int M3_IN2 = 7;
int M3_PWM = 6;

Result:
Motor spins forward for 2 seconds
Then backward for 2 seconds
Repeats forever

